<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-575-865  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 575 865.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  Oct 25 1990 v16 n22 p4(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Plesman Publications Ltd. (Canada) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Unisys appoints new chief. (Brian Clark)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Slofstra, Martin.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Unisys Canada appointed Brian Clark, a 17-year veteran with thecompany, as its vice-president and general manager.andP;  Clark appearsbullish on the company's long-term prospects, despite recentsetbacks for Unisys Corp, its parent company.andP;  Unisys reported afirst quarter loss of $78.7 million and is restructuring andworking on a debt reduction program.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Unisys Canada Inc. (Officials and employees)Unisys Corp. (Finance).andO;Topic:     New AppointmentManagement.andO;Person:    Clark, Brian (Selection and appointment).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Unisys appoints new chiefandM;NORTH YORK, Ont.andP;  -- Unisys Canada has a new man in charge.andM;Brian Clark, a 17-year veteran with the company, became vice-president andgeneral manager of Unisys Canada Inc. earlier this month.andP;  He moved to thesubsidiary after serving as general manager of Unisys New Zealand for thepast five years.andM;Clark joined Unisys in 1973.andP;  He has since held assorted positions ininternational and domestic marketing.andP;  Prior to assuming the senior post inNew Zealand, Clark directed computer systems marketing for the formerAmericas Pacific Division headquartered in Detroit.andM;Clark will report to Edward Blechschmidt, president, Pacific Asia AmericasDivision.andM;In interviews with Computing Canada, both Clark and Blechschmidt, along withJan Gilfillan, vice-president, marketing, Unisys Canada, appeared bullishabout the company's long-term prospects -- despite recent setbacks for UnisysCanada's parent -- Blue Bell, Pa.-based parent Unisys Corp.andM;$78.7 million lossandM;For its first quarter ending March 31, the company reported a loss of $78.7million, citing sluggishness in the U.S.andP;  economy as a major reason.andP;  Unisyshas since embarked on a restructuring and debt reduction program.andM;To restore the company to profitability, Blechschmidt said: &quot;We've achieved alot of commonality between hardware components and that should lower costs.&quot;andM;Blechschmidt's reason for optimism, he said, is Unisys' long-term strategy --a commitment to open systems, to Unix and to international-ratifiedstandards.andP;  &quot;That extends to a lot of things,&quot; he said, &quot;including hardware,software and networking.&quot;andM;Also key is the company's recent announcement of Unisys Architecture (UA)which according to Blechschmidt is &quot;another major benchmark in the bringingtogether of Burroughs and Sperry.&quot;andP;  (Burroughs Inc. and Sperry Corp. mergedin 1985 to form Unisys Corp.).andM;UA, unveiled earlier this month is a framework to help Unisys' customersbuild and operate &quot;open&quot; information networks, according to the company.andM;Although Unisys Canada will not divulge its revenues, Gillfillan said that,as a subsidiary, it is profitable.andP;  Evans Research ranks Unisys fourth on itslist of The Top 100 Companies in the Canadian Computer Industry.andM;Recent successes include a $4.2 million contract to install Unix-basedsystems in each of K Mart's 120 Canadian stores.andP;  &quot;We're making progress,&quot;Gillfillan said.andP;  &quot;If you look at Burroughs and Sperry (in Canada) before themerger, neither were profitable.andP;  Now we are.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>